quently co-exist in the works under discussion, evidence of an earlier culture’s aptitude (now lost) to occupy a position between two stools. Of interest to cultural and literary historians, this ground-breaking study testifies to the arrival of scatology as an academic subject, at the same time recognising that it remains if not outside, then at least at the margins of conventional scholarship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aShakespeare 2018. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aChaucer's fabliaux.  aFreudian theory.  aRochesterian inheritance.  aShakespearean onomastic scatology.  aanality.  acarnivalesque scatology.  acavalier scatology.  aeighteenth century English literature.  ahypochondria.  ainnocent scatology.  amisanthropy.  asexuality.1 aSmith, Peter J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978071909879640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780719098796423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780719098796/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles